<br>
Necro's and SK's get a version of FD that is necromantic in nature.  They way I see it, they use magic to make themselves appear to be a corpse, maybe with a little bit of stink and creepy-crawly worms and bugs thrown in for effect.  Think of them as Voodoo-type guys, doing stuff with zombies and the like.  Their FD is a supernatural sort of thing based on their connection with death-based magic.<br>
<br>
Monk FD skill is completely different.  Monks aren't based on real life oriental monks.  They are based on oriental monks of legend and from Hollywood and Hong Kong films.  One thing that you see in such films is martial artists, particularly ninjas and monks, who can slow their heart rates and breathing so as to appear dead.  Actually, I SAY that EQ monks are based on fictional monks, but I have heard that there are Tibetan monks that can actually do what I have just described and have done it on camera with doctors present.  Of course, if they had included all the stuff from such sources, then monks would be able to turn invisible, walk through walls, reduce their weight to nothing, walk around wearing a wet sheet in sub-zero weather, stop bleeding at will, and kill with a touch.  Monks basically have a very high degree of mind-over-body control that allows them to achieve fantastic things.  Mend is also based on this, by the way.<br>
<br>
Regarding mobility wearing clother/leather versus plate:<br>
<br>
A strong man who has spent his life wearing plate can be surprisingly mobile in it, especially if it is well made armor, BUT if that same man were to take off that armor and go around wearing cloth and leather, he would be even more mobile!  He would never be as mobile as the guy that spent his life studying acrobatics and the like though, even if the acrobat might suck at moving around in plate.  A knight in full plate doesn't just shuffle around like he was wearing a suit made out of lead, but he doesn't win any foot races either and he certainly doesn't go swimming.  In summary, plate mail doesn't turn you into a turtle, but it does have a limiting effect on what you can do.  Realistically, almost nobody, including monks, should be able to swim with their equipment.  If you were to have nothing on but a pair of swim trunks, and then strap a 5 pound sword to your waist, you would have a very hard time swimming, especially if you had to swim any great distance.  A monk with a 2hb staff, a bunch of bags and maybe a backpack or two, etc., etc., isn't going to be able to swim very well either.  But EQ is a game, where thankfully realism is suspended enough to let us have fun.<br>
<br>
In summary, trying to base what EQ characters can and can't do on real life analogs just doesn't work.  If it did, then monks would be the fastest running, highest jumping characters in the game, except for naked people going on corpse recoveries.  There would be no such thing as hitpoints.  In a real fight, if I stab you through the heart or dash your brains out with a club, the number of &quot;hitpoints&quot; you have doesn't really matter.  Get it?  <br>
<br>
I have to say that the person that started this thread is just trolling.  The title seems to be saying, &quot;Let's just stop arguing about this, okay?  Give peace a chance!&quot;, but the body of his posting basically says, &quot;We should all stop arguing about this because I am right and you are wrong and and also stupid and this is why and if you disagree with me, you are just being argumentative!&quot;<br>
 <p>Argfeld<BR>
Level 58 Monk<BR>
Order of the Scattered Winds<BR>
Bertoxxulous<BR>
