I don't know about monks being able to jump really high though, but I'd have to brush up on some old movies / etc. For the most part it seems people like to mesh ninja into their class. Monk-Ninjas, Rogue-Ninjas (gg class title assassin), etc. Yea, if you were a ninja from the movies I could understand you leaping buildings and running roofs, but I don't recall ever seeing monks leaping high. They are more mental than acrobatic (correct me if I'm wrong).<br>
<br>
Personally, I think weight affecting movement / swimming would be a cool concept. Although I do not agree that warriors would move as slow as some people think. I think people picture a lawyer in a suit of armor and how he would move when they think warrior in plate, when thats not the least bit accurate. Of course I also don't consider warrior the most plate-dependent class RP-wise, I'd give that title to the Knight, whom usually addorns heavy plate armor for looks more than battle. A warrior would be more of a plate / leather combo -- a balance of vital protection and ability to move around the battlefield. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uaielmankajiraliege.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aielman KajiraLiege</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 48<br> <font color=#FF0000>(10/16/02 6:10:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1415.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fallenalliance.org/screenshots/downwpst.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_ac.gif" align=absmiddle>  Let's shed some light on a common misconception...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Regarding mobility wearing clother/leather versus plate:<br>
<br>
A strong man who has spent his life wearing plate can be surprisingly mobile in it, especially if it is well made armor, BUT if that same man were to take off that armor and go around wearing cloth and leather, he would be even more mobile! <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
A common misconception perpetuated by Hollywood and ignorance of fact is that plate armor is exceedingly heavy and seriously limits mobility.<br>
<br>
That's completely wrong. Plate armor, since around 1270, has been lighter than any other form of armor. Correct me if I'm wroing, because it's been a few years since I studied this, but the blast furnace was invented in about 1270. Since that time, steel has been able to be manufactured in such a way to make it strong and relatively light. The main reason plate armor was the choice of the nobility and well to do was that it afforded you the same kind of protection that full chain/scale did, but at a fraction of the weight. In addition, full plate, if properly fitted and equipped, leaves you with nearly full mobility. I know this because I've worn it...both old armor and new armor (the old armor was, btw, better made and lighter, surprisingly). I've also fought in it at SCA events and RenFests. Chain is Much heavier and far more confining. I chain skirt (covers chest, shoulders, back and the upper thigh)weighs upwards of 60 pounds and that doesn't include helmut or anything to cover your arms. the weight of it is also carried squrely on the shoulders alone. A full suit of plate (chest, back, arms, neck, shoulders, wrists, upper and lower legs, boots,  and hands) weighs less than 50 lbs with helm (usually the heaviest individual armor piece) depending on the style and can be even less with a small helmut. In addition, plate distrubutes the weight about the body which makes it seem alot lighter too. I have seen guys vault onto the back of a horse wearing full tilting plate (minus helm) which is the heaviest grade of plate they ever made. There were also accounts of Knights swimming across rivers wearing full armor to get to or running away from battles in the past. As a point of fact, the heaviest individual pieces of a warrior's panoply has always been the shield, if he used one, with the weapon he carried being next. The only piece of plate armor that was ever truly heavy was the tilting helm used for jousting. Those mothers can weigh up to 30 lbs all by themselves...but then again, having a tree trunk rammed into your face at the double gallop speed in the lists sort of demanded that heavy of protection.<br>
<br>
Now...this isn't to say that plate is as light or unrestricting as monk robes, but it's certainly not that confining nor debilitating to your movement and sure as hell will offer a helluva lot more protection against edged/blunt weapons. <br>
<br>
Prior comments were made that they're magic pajamas...ok...fine. But I have a magic buick strapped around my body and the enhancement to your pajama's is no greater than the enhancement to the destroyer worth of metal i'm wearing...which still means the plate should Still mitigate much more.<br>
<br>
peace,<br>
Aielman KajiraLiege<br>
